<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Distribution_by_value  
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value">
<b>Distribution_by_value</b> provides a numerical definition of a probability distribution as a list of index/value pairs.

<note number="1"> <b>Distribution_by_value</b> is used where there is no named distribution which can be used to identify the distribution, for
example, when the distribution is derived from observation.
</note>

</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Distribution_by_value  Attribute: distribution_function 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value.distribution_function"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value.distribution_function">
The <b>distribution_function</b> identifies the type of function which the index/value list represents.

<note number="2">Probabilities may be described by a number of different types of functions, such as the cumulative distribution function, the probability density function for
continuous distributions or the probability generation function for discrete distributions. Each function is identified through reference data.</note>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Distribution_by_value  Attribute: has_values 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value.has_values"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Distribution_by_value.has_values">
<b>Has_values</b> is a list of index/value pairs, where the value of index increases strictly monotonically along the list. It
represents a numerical approximation to a probability distribution.
<example number="1"> The distribution is the probability generating function for an unfair dice ((1,0.1), (2,0.166),...,(6,0.23)).
Here each pair represents the value on the face and the probability of it occuring.
The probability of rolling a 1 or a 2 is therefore (0.1 + 0.166). </example>
<example number="2"> The distribution is a cumulative distribution function for the measured length of a component ((2.1, 0.0), (2.2, 0.1), (2.3, 0.6), (2.4, 1.0))
Here each pair represents a length and the probability that the component exceeds that length. The probability that the component
is between 2.2m and 2.3m long is therefore (0.6 - 0.1). </example>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Parameter  
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Parameter"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Parameter">
A <b>Parameter</b> provides on of the set of values that characterises a probability distribution.
<example number="3"> The Normal (or Gaussian) distribution has, in the standard parameterisation, two parameters: the mean and the varaince </example>
<note number="3">For many common, the mean and the variance are sufficient to characterise a distribution, and the parameter list may be empty.</note>
</ext_description>


