<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution">
A probability distribution relates all possible outcomes of an observation on a given system with the probability of their occuring.
<note number="8"> For a full understanding of probability distribution and the terms used, a textbook on probability theory should be consulted.</note>
<note number="9"> This entity describes a particular probability distribution, rather than the general type of distribution. For example, in
coin tossing experiment, the number of heads that may occur is given by a binomial distribution - that is, a type of distribution, and outside the scope of this module.
An experiment of, say, 10 tosses of a particular coin will give a distribution with an average of 5 heads, and with 67% of experiments lying in the range3 to 7 heads. This module
allows such calculations to be made. The actual probability of an outcome, say 6 heads in 10 tosses, is recorded using the probability module.</note>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: description 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.description"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.description">
A description of the distribution.
<note number="10">The description can be used to describe any particularites of the system the distribution describes. </note>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: distibution_name 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.distibution_name"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.distibution_name">
The name of the type of distribution that the distribution is taken from.
<note number="11"> The name is taken from reference data, which is based on the standard mathematical names for distributions, such
as "Binomial", "Normal", "Guassian", etc. Empirically derived distributions will not normally be named. </note>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: id 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.id"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.id">
A unique identifier for the distribution.
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: is_continuous 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.is_continuous"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.is_continuous">
<b>Is_continuous</b>is used to distinguish continous distributions from discrete distributions.
<example number="4">The measurement of a persons height is a continuous distribution, since it can take any value between 0 and 3m.</example>
<example number="5">Coin tossing gives rise to a discrete distribution, since the number of heads cannot be a fraction.</example>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: mean 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.mean"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.mean">
The mean is a mathematical property of a probability distribution, and this attribute holds the value for the distribution.
<note number="12"> Mean is generally what is thought of as the "average" value.</note>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_distribution_arm  Entity: Probability_distribution  Attribute: name 
   <express_ref linkend="probability_distribution:arm:Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.name"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_distribution_arm.Probability_distribution.name">
The name of the particular distribution.
<note number="13"> The name provides a cue to the particular source of the distribution, such as "A fair coin tossed 10 times",
rather than the type of distribution (in this case Binomial) which is given by the <b>distribution_name</b> attribute.</note>
</ext_description>


<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
